  {"domain":"Reading","skill":"Key Ideas & Details","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">A teaspoon of healthy soil contains more microorganisms than there are people on Earth, and farmers are learning to treat that invisible livestock as carefully as any herd. Fields planted with the same crop year after year show depleted microbial diversity; rotating corn with legumes, by contrast, feeds nitrogen-fixing bacteria that fertilize the soil naturally. In trials, rotated fields required a third less synthetic fertilizer while matching conventional yields. The soil microbiome, once an afterthought, is becoming the quiet foundation of sustainable farm economics.</em>The passage indicates that legumes benefit soil because they","choices":["feed bacteria that fix nitrogen.","shade the ground.","absorb extra water.","repel insects."],"correct":0},
  {"domain":"Reading","skill":"Integration of Knowledge & Ideas","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">A teaspoon of healthy soil contains more microorganisms than there are people on Earth, and farmers are learning to treat that invisible livestock as carefully as any herd. Fields planted with the same crop year after year show depleted microbial diversity; rotating corn with legumes, by contrast, feeds nitrogen-fixing bacteria that fertilize the soil naturally. In trials, rotated fields required a third less synthetic fertilizer while matching conventional yields. The soil microbiome, once an afterthought, is becoming the quiet foundation of sustainable farm economics.</em>The passage’s economic argument is that healthy soil microbiomes","choices":["raise crop prices for consumers.","only matter to scientists.","make farming more expensive.","lower input costs while maintaining yields."],"correct":3}
